Nvidia Corporation, founded in 1993 by Jensen Huang, Chris Malachowsky, and Curtis Priem, began as a company focused on creating graphics processing units (GPUs) for gaming and multimedia. Headquartered in Santa Clara, California, Nvidia gained prominence in 1999 with the release of the GeForce 256, marketed as the world’s first GPU. This innovation revolutionized the gaming industry and established Nvidia as a leader in visual computing.

Throughout the 2000s, Nvidia expanded its product line and influence, acquiring rival 3dfx's assets and introducing the CUDA programming model in 2006, which allowed GPUs to be used for general-purpose computing. This move laid the groundwork for Nvidia’s expansion into fields beyond gaming, including scientific computing, artificial intelligence (AI), and data centers.

In the 2010s, Nvidia’s GPUs became essential for AI and machine learning applications, particularly with the rise of deep learning. Products like the Tesla and later A100 GPUs powered high-performance computing in research and enterprise sectors. The company also entered the automotive market with its DRIVE platform, advancing self-driving car technology.

By the 2020s, Nvidia had become a dominant force in AI and data center markets, fueled further by the popularity of generative AI. In 2020, Nvidia announced a planned acquisition of ARM Holdings, though the deal was later abandoned in 2022 due to regulatory challenges.

Today, Nvidia remains at the forefront of GPU and AI computing, with its technologies powering gaming, professional visualization, cloud computing, and AI research worldwide.

claude
